				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Sorry for ressurrecting a dead topic, but I would like to shed some new light on the situation.
<br />
<br />I don't think anyone here is really seeing the ramifications of this project. Having this game on an NES cartridge would be life-altering for thousands, if not hundreds of thousands of people. For example, Capcom released a press release kit for MM9. It was an actual NES cartridge, but they had hollowed it out and simply put in a mini-CD with screenshots from the game. Basically, it just LOOKED like would-be nes cartridge but had no game and was completely unplayable. The press release kit was selling for $1200 on eBay, making it one of the most sought-after promotional items in videogame history. $1200 for a hollow nes cartridge with just the MM9 sticker on the front! Fans thought that sticker was worth the price of what a lot of people pay for a new HDTV. (<!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.capcomdigital.com/blog/2008/09/16/mega_man_9_retail_package">http://www.capcomdigital.com/blog/2008/ ... il_package</a><!-- m -->)
<br />
<br />In saying this, I'm not trying to advertise how much money would be made off an actuall NES cartridge. Obviously that is illegal to sell it and that is not my goal from the project. I only say this so anyone who thought they would receive no recognition beyond a "hey good job" pat on the back from this forum, you are wrong. Making an nes cartridge of this game would basically make you the god of all mega man fans worldwide. The entire online retro gaming community would be going nuts.
<br />
<br />Also, for those who argue this will hurt MM9 sales, you are right. If a rom is released of the game, many will opt out of buying the game since the rom would be free. My argument against this is as follows:
<br />
<br />1. The hysteria for MM9 is over. It's been out for almost a year now and I'm sure sales are slow.
<br />2. I can't imagine Capcom would be at all upset about this. They actually REALLY wanted to make a cartridge of the game (see the link I posted above), but publicly they couldn't do it because of all the legal hoops they would have to jump through as a company to actually sell that cartridge in stores. I'm sure the producers of the game would shed a tear or two of joy if one of their fans made the cartridge, since the entire premise of the game was designed with the NES in mind every step of the way.
<br />
<br />As far as current progress on this project, I found a guy who is currently working on this. I'm sure it's a lot of work though and he would love some help. If you want to help out, his email is dlm92887 at yahoo dot com. Basically what the plan is is to extract the graphics from the wii .wad file, and then reprogram a very similar rom like MM2 or 3, and then flash it on an NES cartridge.
<br />
<br />If anyone is interesting in helping, I'm sure we could put a portmm9 website together and starting dividing responsibilities.
<br />
<br />Anyway, I've said enough.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

