						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">wildonrio wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't think anyone here is really seeing the ramifications of this project. Having this game on an NES cartridge would be life-altering for thousands, if not hundreds of thousands of people.<br /><br />...<br /><br />Making an nes cartridge of this game would basically make you the god of all mega man fans worldwide. The entire online retro gaming community would be going nuts.</div><br />Extremely hyperbolic.  This isn't "life-altering" or putting anyone at godhood.  Most people would probably just shrug at the nerds with too much time on their hands, especially since a) it's not officially official from Capcom, b) it's not being sold in stores or in any quantity that they could reasonably expect to own it.  And a lot of people threw out their NESs long ago.<br /><br />Nobody goes nuts over homebrew for ancient systems, recognizable character or not.  Remember Somari, how that shook the foundations of the gaming community?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Also, for those who argue this will hurt MM9 sales, you are right. If a rom is released of the game, many will opt out of buying the game since the rom would be free. My argument against this is as follows:<br /><br />1. The hysteria for MM9 is over. It's been out for almost a year now and I'm sure sales are slow.<br />2. I can't imagine Capcom would be at all upset about this. They actually REALLY wanted to make a cartridge of the game (see the link I posted above), but publicly they couldn't do it because of all the legal hoops they would have to jump through as a company to actually sell that cartridge in stores. I'm sure the producers of the game would shed a tear or two of joy if one of their fans made the cartridge, since the entire premise of the game was designed with the NES in mind every step of the way.</div><br />So your argument is that infringing on copyright is ok because<br /><br />1. They've already made their money<br />2. They wouldn't really care, would they?  We'd be doing them a favor!<br /><br />Seriously?  You cannot base issues of legality on this reasoning.  I'm sure sales of Whitney Houston CDs are slow now too, so I guess it's ok to share them with P2P?  Plus it'd help raise her popularity, bring her back into the public consciousness!  What a great idea.<br /><br />You said it yourself about all the legal hoops Capcom would have to jump through.  We're somehow above those same laws?  I guess it's harder for a large company to break the law and not get caught than a small group...<br /><br />EDIT: Oh dear, I don't wish to make fun of anyone, but I hope you're not really expecting to work on it with this person from that wiihack site:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">thedrizzle420 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">email me all the info u find and i will help i love all the megaman games ill put all my power into makeing it for u and put it up 4 a download k</div></div>

